{
  "analysis": "The log file itself may be owned by root or have wrong permissions. Let's check the file inside /var/log/mailman3 and ensure list user can write. Also maybe the service script is not using the correct user. We can try to start mailman master directly using mailman command with --run-as-root and appropriate config. Since mailman command works (we saw earlier with --run-as-root lists). We can start the master runner in the background. But first we need to ensure the configuration file has site_owner set. Let's update /etc/mailman3/mailman.cfg with site_owner and maybe other settings. We'll also need to set subscription policy for list later. Let's first edit the config file.",
  "plan": "1. Edit /etc/mailman3/mailman.cfg to set site_owner to something like root@local.edu. 2. Ensure LMTP settings are correct. 3. Check postfix configuration for LMTP. 4. Start mailman master using mailman start --run-as-root. 5. Create the reading-group list. 6. Set subscription policy to open. 7. Update /etc/aliases and run newaliases. Let's start with editing config.",
